{ The King is a strong piece To those of us who worry about the safety of
the King, Tal’s play in this game is a joy and a revelation. Tal realizes
that the power of the King increases as the game progresses and as the pieces come flying off the board. By the time the ending has been reached, the
King is truly a formidable fighting piece. Watch Tal’s King stroll non chalantly into the heart of the enemy camp, gather up a couple of Pawns, and then prepare to escort one of his own Pawns to the Queening square. It is a treat to watch, an absorbing lesson in endgame procedure. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. f4 Nc6 { Black avoids a trap with this move, indicating that one must not play
mechanically even at this early stage. } (6... Bg7? 7. e5 Nh5 (7... dxe5? 8. fxe5 Ng4 (8... Nh5 9. g4) 9. Bb5+ Kf8 (9... Bd7 10. Qxg4) 10. Ne6+) 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. e6 fxe6 10. Nxe6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qc8 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Ng5 Qxc3+ 14. Bd2) 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. exd6 exd6 10. Be3 { Other lines of play look more aggressive, but lead to no more than
equality. For example } (10. Qe2+ Be7 11. Be3 O-O) (10. Qd4 Nf6 11. Be3 Be7 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O c5) 10... Be7 11. Qf3 d5 12. O-O-O Bf6 13. Bd4 { Proper development does not concern itself merely with placing
the pieces where they are effective for attack. It is equally important to
interfere with the range of influence of the opponent’s pieces. You must dispute control, as Tal does here, of every file, rank and diagonal. } { [%csl Rf6] } 13... O-O 14. h4 { Indicating his intention of opening up the h-file by
15 h5. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gh5g6] } 14... Rb8 { Black seizes an open file. Captur ing the h-Pawn instead would
be dangerous, as after } { [%csl Rd4] } (14... Bxh4 15. Qh3 g5 16. g3 Nf6 17. f5 { [%csl Rh4] }) 15. Qf2 Rb4 16. Bxf6 { Tal is not tempted by the offer of a Pawn. It is easy to yield and then
fall into something like this: } (16. Bxa7 Qa5 17. Be3 Rxb2 18. Kxb2 Bxc3+ 19. Kc1 Qa3+ 20. Kb1 Qb2#) 16... Nxf6 17. a3 { Here too Tal resists temptation } (17. Qxa7 Qd6 18. g3 Rxb2 19. Kxb2 Qb4+ 20. Kc1 Qxc3 $40 { Black has a strong attack, one threat for example being }) 17... Qb6 18. Qxb6 Rxb6 19. Na4! { A powerful move, even though the Knight moves to
the side of the board. Tal has two objects in mind: To fix Black’s center
Pawns so that they may not advance, and to dominate his opponent’s weakened black squares. } { [%csl Yc5,Rc6,Yd4,Rd5] } 19... Rb7 20. Bd3 Nh5 21. Rhf1 Re7 22. f5! { A fine positional sacrifice. At the cost of a Pawn Tal disrupts his
opponent’s Pawn structure on the King side. In addition to this, the
acceptance of the sacrifice leaves Black’s Bishop hemmed in by Pawns occupying white squares. } 22... gxf5 { Black is hypnotized into taking the Pawn, and that leads to
his ruin. } { [%csl Rc8] } 23. Rfe1 { Another fine positional move. Tal is a Pawn behind, but does
not hesitate to exchange pieces. The point is that he must dispute control
of the open e-file, or else Black will double Rooks and gain complete possession of it. } { [%cal Ge1e8] } 23... Rfe8 24. Rxe7 Rxe7 25. Kd2! { The beginning of a remarkable tour. The King is headed for the Queen side
where it will terrorize all the Pawns in sight. } 25... Ng3 26. Kc3 f4 { Clears the way for the Bishop to come into the game. } { [%csl Yc8] } 27. Kd4 { The King continues his journey along the black squares. } 27... Bf5 28. Rd2 Re6 { [%csl Yc6,Rh4][%cal Ge6h6] } 29. Nc5 Rh6 30. Ke5 Bxd3 31. cxd3 Rxh4 32. Kd6 { The King goes merrily on his way. } 32... Rh6+ 33. Kc7 { Despite the fact that he is two Pawns down, White’s chances
are better in the ending. His King is so wonderfully active, and Black’s so
woefully passive, that he is in effect a King ahead! } { [%csl Gc7] } 33... Nf5 34. Kb7 Nd4 { The Knight guards the c-Pawn, freeing
the Rook for active duty. Black threatens now 35 … ♖h2 followed by 36 … f3,
winning another Pawn and the game. } { [%csl Yc6,Gh6][%cal Gh6h2,Yf4f3] } 35. Rf2 a5 36. Rxf4 Ne6 37. Rg4+ Kf8 (37... Rg6 38. Rxg6+ hxg6 39. Nxe6 fxe6 40. Kxc6 Kf7 41. b4 $18) 38. Kxc6! { The King fears nothing - not even discovered
check. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Yh6c6] } 38... Nxc5+ 39. Kxc5 Re6 40. Kxd5 { (One must resolutely avoid the impulse to say, “The Pawns fall like ripe
apples.”) } 40... Rb6 41. b4 axb4 42. axb4 Ke7 43. Kc5 Rf6 44. Rd4 { This cuts off Black’s King from the Queen
side, and the possibility of blocking the passed Pawn } { [%csl Gb4,Re7][%cal Gd4d8] } 44... Rf5+ 45. Kb6! (45. Rd5 Rf4 $132 { [%cal Gf4g4] }) 45... Rf6+ 46. Kc7 Rf5 47. Re4+ { Drives the King still farther away from the Queen side. } 47... Kf6 { [%cal Ge4e8] } 48. Kc6 Rf2 49. g4 h5 { Black sacrifices one Pawn to make a passed Pawn of the other. There was
nothing in 49 … ♖c2+, as after the reply 50 ♖c4, Black has simply wasted a
move. } (49... Rc2+ 50. Rc4) 50. gxh5 Kg5 51. b5 f5 52. Rb4 f4 53. b6 f3 54. b7 { 1-0 Black resigns. } (54. Rc2+ Kd5 55. f2 b8=Q 56. f1=Q Qg3+ 57. Kf6 (57. Kf5 Qg6#) 57... Qg6+ 58. Ke7 Rb7+ { [%csl Re7] }) 1-0


