{ Aggressive Rook in the Ending Tarrasch plays the following game as though
he were giving a good friend a lesson in the art of winning an ending. “In
a Rook and Pawn ending,” Tarrasch used to say, “the Rook must be used aggres sively. It must either attack enemy Pawns, or give active support to the
advance of one its own Pawns to the Queening square.” Here, with the help of an active Rook that keeps the opponent under unremitting pressure, Tarrasch’s King and passed Pawn march methodically up the chessboard. As they move forward step by step, the opponent’s pieces are driven further and further
back until they reach the very edge of the board. There, they can put up little resistance to the inexorable advance of the passed Pawn. The classic simplicity of Tarrasch’s technique in the conduct of this ending is so impressive as to make it in my opinion: The Most Instructive Rook and Pawn Ending Ever Played. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 { Tarrasch prefers this to the usual 3 ♘c3, since the Knight is developed
without blocking the c- Pawn. } (3. exd5) (3. e5) (3. Nc3) 3... c5 (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6] }) (3... Nf6) 4. exd5 Qxd5 (4... exd5 { [editor's note: is entirely playable but will lead to an IQP for Black] } 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nb3 Bd6) (4... cxd4? 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. dxe6! Bxb5 7. exf7+ { [%csl Rb5,Re8,Rg8][%cal Yd1h5] } (7. Qh5 { [%csl Rb5,Rf7] } 7... Qe7 8. Qxb5+ $14)) 5. Ngf3 { A temporary Pawn sacrifice, to gain time for quick development of the
pieces. } 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 Qh5 (6... Qd8) (6... Qd6 7. O-O Nf6 8. Nb3 Nc6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7) 10... a6 11. Re1 Qc7) 7. O-O Nc6 (7... e5? 8. Nxe5 Qxd1 (8... Qxe5 9. Re1) 9. Bxf7+ Ke7 10. Rxd1) 8. Nb3 { With a triple attack on the d-Pawn. } 8... e5 9. Nxe5! { [%csl Rh5] } 9... Qxd1 { Other captures lose instantly } (9... Qxe5 10. Re1) (9... Nxe5 10. Qxh5) 10. Rxd1 Nxe5 11. Re1 { This pin, followed by 12 f4, will regain the piece given up by White. } 11... f6 12. f4 Bb4 { Not merely a developing move, this attack on the Rook must be met
carefully, if White is to avoid being forced into a draw. } 13. Bd2 (13. Re2 Bg4 14. Re4 Bf5 15. Re2 Bg4 { allows Black to draw by his perpetual attack on the Rook. }) 13... Bxd2 14. Nxd2 Bf5 15. fxe5 O-O-O { Best, since the King reaches com parative safety while the Queen Rook
comes into play } 16. Bd3 { [%csl Rf5] } (16. Rac1) 16... Bxd3 17. cxd3 { White benefits in two ways by the exchange of pieces: he is rid of
Black’s active Bishop, and he has an open file for his Queen Rook. } 17... fxe5 18. Rac1+! { This prevents the King from moving toward the center for the ending. If
he does so by } 18... Kb8 { [%csl Rb8,Yd4,Yd5,Ye4,Ye5][%cal Gc1c8] } (18... Kd7? 19. Rxe5 Kd6 20. Re4 Kd5 21. Rc4 { and White wins the d-Pawn. }) 19. Rxe5 Nf6 20. Rce1 (20. Re7 Rd7 21. Rxd7 Nxd7 22. Rc4) 20... Rhe8 (20... Rd7 21. Re7 Rhd8 { gives Black a fair chance to hold the game }) 21. Rxe8 Nxe8 (21... Rxe8 22. Rxe8+ Nxe8 23. Nb3 { follows, and White wins a Pawn. }) 22. Re7! { Rook on the Seventh Rank. A paralyzing move! Black must submit to the
loss of a Pawn. } 22... a6 23. Nb3 { [%cal Yb3a5] } 23... b6 { To prevent the Knight from coming in at a5 } { [%csl Rb3] } (23... Ka7 24. Na5 Rb8 25. Nc6+ $18) 24. Nxd4 Rxd4 25. Rxe8+ Kc7 { White is a Pawn ahead, and that should be sufficient to win. If he is
