pieces. } (29. f3 { [%csl Rf3] }) 29... Kf7 30. Ba6 Qb8 31. Nb5! { This attack on the Rook (which has no safe square to run to) forces an
exchange of Bishop for Knight. } 31... Bxb5 32. Bxb5 { The foregoing exchange of pieces highlights certain features in the
position: (1) The disappearance of Black’s Queen Bishop (which travelled on
white squares) accentuates the weakness of Black’s white squares. Tarrasch can now settle pieces on those squares without fear of their being
dislodged. (2) Black’s remaining Bishop is completely imprisoned by Pawns standing on black squares. (3) Black’s King cannot flee to safety by way of e8. (4) White has two active Bishops against Black’s two ineffectual Knights } 32... Rfc8 33. hxg5 hxg5 34. Bc6! { Blockade! The Rooks are doubled on the open file, but can make no use of
it. } 34... Bf8 35. Qf3! { [%csl Rg5][%cal Ge3g5,Yf3f7] } 35... Rxc6 (35... Kg6? 36. Rgh2 Ne7 (36... Rd8 37. Rh8 Be7 38. R1h7 { [%cal Gf3f5] } 38... Qc8)) 36. dxc6 Ne6 37. Rh7+ Bg7 (37... Ke8 38. Qf5 Nf4 39. Bxf4 gxf4 40. Qd7#) 38. Ng3 Rxc6 39. Nf5! { Finally the Knight arrives at the ideal square! } 39... Qc8 40. Rgh2 Ne7 (40... Kg6 41. Bxg5 fxg5 (41... Nxg5 42. Rxg7#) 42. Ne7+! (42. Nh4+! Kxh7 43. Qf5+ Kh8 44. Ng6#) 42... Nxe7 43. R2h6+ Bxh6 44. Qf7#) 41. Nxg7 Nxg7 42. Bxg5 { [%csl Rf6,Rg7][%cal Gf3f6,Gg5h6] } 42... Qe6 { Showalter made this move and then resigned without waiting for a reply. } (42... Bxf6 { or the more interesting } 43. Qxf6 Rxg7+ 44. Ke6 (44. Kxg7 Rh7+ 45. Kg6 Rh6+ { [%csl Rf6] }) 44... Rxe7+! 45. Kxe7 (45. Qxe7 Qf5#) 45... Rh7+ 46. Ke6 Qb3+ 47. d5 Qxd5#) (42... Bh6 { [%csl Rg7] }) 1-0


