{ Bishop & pawn ending Deluxe Blackburne lost his first round game against
Weiss in the great New York Tournament of 1889, but got his revenge when
the players met again in the second round. What made the victory particularly sweet was the fact that Blackburne achieved it by using the very weapons
with which he was beaten - Bishop and Pawns against Bishop and Pawns. It is doubtful that even Rubinstein in his palmiest days could have played the ending in more convincing style. }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Qxd5 4. Nc3 (4. c4) 4... Qa5 5. Nf3 c6 { A safety measure, to provide a retreat for the Queen. } { [%csl Ya5] } 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nc4 Qd8 { Sorrowful homecoming, but 7 … ♕b4 loses the Queen by 8 a3, while 7 … ♕a6
does likewise by 8♘d6+ and 9 ♗xa6. } (7... Qb4 8. a3) (7... Qa6 8. Nd6+) (7... Qc7) 8. Be2 g6 9. d5 { Simple development by 9 ♗e3 was preferable. The exchanges that now follow
will increase the scope of Black’s King Bishop. } (9. Be3) 9... cxd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 Bg7 12. h4 { This may have been meant to discourage King side Castling, but it doesn’t
disturb Blackburne,who goes about his business. } 12... O-O 13. h5 Nf6 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Bd3 Be6 17. Bd2 Rac8 { The Rook develops with gain of tempo - the threat of winning a
piece by 18 … ♗xc4. } { [%csl Rc4] } 18. Ne5 Nd7 { Forces an exchange which favors Black, all of whose pieces are in active
play. } 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20. Bc1 { A wretched move, but how else can White save his b-Pawn? } (20. O-O-O? Rxd3) (20. Bc3 Rxc3 21. bxc3 Bxc3+ 22. Ke2 Bxa1 23. Rxa1) 20... Bc4! { A fine move which wins a Pawn. } 21. Rh3 (21. Bxc4 Rxc4 22. c3 Rxc3 23. bxc3 Bxc3+ { [%csl Gb7,Ge7] }) 21... Bxd3 22. Rxd3 Rxd3 23. cxd3 Rc2! { Rook on the seventh - a paralyzing move! } { [%csl Gc2] } 24. Rb1 Bd4 { Black’s Rook and Bishop work beautifully together,
attacking Pawns on both sides of the board. } { [%csl Yc2,Yd4] } 25. Bd2 Rxb2 (25... Bxb2? 26. Kd1 { [%csl Rb2,Rc2] }) (25... Bxf2+!? 26. Kd1 Rc6) 26. Rxb2 { White has no choice. If he avoids the exchange of Rooks by playing 26 ♖a1
