{ That Old Black Magic This is the finest game I know of to reveal the
mysteries of the black squares. In this game, White gets a strangle-hold on
the position through his control of the black squares. His opponent’s Pawns are held in a grip of steel, and are unable to move without loss. The
consequence is that the pieces behind the Pawns are helpless to come into the game. White’s pieces, on the other hand, are unrestrained, and free to roam all over the board. The exploitation of White’s su periority is quite entertaining, the King himself giving a remarkable display of his
powers in the ending }
1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 Nc6 { This cannot be bad, since a piece is developed. More to the point though,
