{ Odyssey of a Isolated Pawn An isolated Pawn looks anemic, and generally
is a weakling. Tartakover used to say, “An isolated Pawn spreads gloom all
over the chess board.” And this only confirmed what Philidor had said, many years before Tartakover was born, “A Pawn, when separated from his
fellows, will seldom or never make a fortune.” That an isolated Pawn can become dangerous though (especially if it becomes a passed Pawn) is the theme of this fascinating game. As the number of pieces on the board diminishes, the power of the Pawn increases, and with every step it takes, its
menace becomes greater. The entire army of the enemy may be tied up trying to halt its progress. Znosko-Borovsky’s masterly treat ment of his isolated Pawn in the game that follows elicited Lasker’s admiring comment, “It is a game of classic simplicity and beauty.” }
