{ Escorting the potential Queen “The winning of a Pawn among good players
of even strength,” says Capablanca, “often means the winning of the game.”
The extra Pawn can be turned into a Queen, as the good player knows, and with a Queen ahead he can beat anybody in the world. The technique of
transforming a Pawn into a Queen is shown more simply, clearly and concisely in the following game than in any other game I know. Watch particularly how Schlechter makes use of his King to escort the passed Pawn up the board. Note how the King zig-zags alongside the Pawn,protecting it from attack,
while himself evading checks by the Rook. The method once learned is not easily forgotten. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 { Black should not give up the center, but play to maintain a strong point
at e5. [Editor's note: these days this is usually brought about by the move
order e4 d6 d4 Nf6 Nc3 e5 Nf3, as here attempts to transpose to the Main line Philidor, hoping White plays a consequent Nc3, meet sharper lines]: } (3... Nd7 4. Bc4 c6 5. O-O Be7 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Ng5 Bxg5 8. Qh5 { wins the B pair }) (3... Nf6 4. dxe5 Nxe4 5. Qd5 Nc5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. exd6 Qxd6 8. Nc3 { where White is known to have a small edge }) 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bd7 6. Be2 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 { The drawback to Black’s un -enterprising system of defense is that his
pieces tend to get in each other’s way. The Pawn position in the center
(White Pawn at e4 against Black’s at d6) indicates White’s pieces will have greater freedom of movement. } 8. f4 { Further restraint on Black’s game! White’s e-Pawn and f-Pawn prevent
Black from occupying the center with his pieces. And without a say in the
center, it will be difficult for Black to equalize. } 8... Nxd4 { This attempt to get some freedom by exchanging pieces only helps White,
whose Queen assumes a dominating position in the center. } 9. Qxd4 Bc6 10. b4! { A good move! It helps White’s development (his Bishop
will come into the game at b2) and interferes with Black’s (his Bishop will
be driven back by b5). } { [%cal Gb4b5,Gc1b2] } 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Ne8 { [%cal Gf7f5] } (11... Qd7 { cuts off the Bishop’s retreat, and would cost the life of that piece
after } 12. b5 { Black therefore plays to get in the freeing move … f5. }) 12. b5 Bd7 (12... Bf6 { (to drive the Queen off) would be a mistake } 13. e5 dxe5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. bxc6 { wins a piece for White. }) 13. Nd5 f5 14. Bd3 c6 { The menacing Knight must be evicted, even though the d-Pawn is
weakened thereby. } { [%csl Rd5] } 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 { [%csl Rd6] } 17. Rae1! { A strong developing move! The Rook comes into the game with a threat - 18
exf5, winning a Pawn. } 17... fxe4 { This capture must be made, if the Pawn is to be saved, even though it
increases the range of White’s pieces } 18. Rxe4 Qf6 (18... Qd8 19. Rxe8 Bxe8 20. Qxg7#) (18... Qf7 19. Rfe1 Nf6 20. Re7 Qh5 (20... Qd5 21. Bc4) 21. Rxd7) 19. Qc4+ Qf7 (19... d5 20. Bxf6 dxc4 21. Bxc4+ Kh8 22. Be7 Rf5 23. Rd1 Bc8 24. g4 Ra5 25. Bd8 { [%csl Ra5,Re8] }) 20. Re7! { And the Rook comes in still further! Its control of the seventh rank will
net at least a Pawn for White, while retaining the superior position. What
more could anyone ask? } 20... Qxc4 21. Bxc4+ d5 22. Bxd5+ cxd5 23. Rxd7 { White has gained a Pawn in the melee. Now he must utilize his superiority
in material by promoting the extra Pawn to a Queen. } 23... Rc8 24. Rf2 Rc4 25. Rxd5 Rcxf4 26. Rxf4 Rxf4 27. Rd8 Kf8 28. Ba3+ Kf7 29. Rd7+ Kg6 (29... Ke6? 30. Re7+) 30. Rxa7 Rc4 31. Re7 Nf6 32. Re2 { Saves the c-Pawn, but can he do the same for the a-Pawn? } 32... Ra4 33. Bb2 { Answer: He does not even try! White is willing to return one of the extra
Pawns if he can thereby bring about another exchange of pieces. One Pawn
ahead, in a simple Rook and Pawn ending, is all he wants! } 33... Rxa2 34. Bxf6 Kxf6 35. Kf2 { The King starts out for the Queen side, to give the c-Pawn protection as
it moves up the board. Black’s King can take little or no part in the
proceedings, as it is cut off from the Queen side. } 35... h5 (35... Ra5 36. Ke1 Re5 37. Rxe5 Kxe5 38. Kd2 Kd4 39. c3+ Kc4 40. Kc2 Kc5 41. Kd3 Kd5 42. c4+ Kc5 43. Kc3 { The idea, in this and similar cases, is simple: the passed
Pawn keeps Black occupied, and allows White time to go after the deserted
Pawns. } { [%csl Rg7,Rh7] }) 36. Ke1 (36. Ke3 { shuts off the action of the Rook and permits Black’s King to
cross over to the Queen side. } { [%cal Re2e8] }) 36... g5 37. Kd2 Kf5 38. Kd3 Ra8 { Black hopes to make matters difficult for White’s rather exposed King,
who must stay near the passed Pawn, while evading checks by the Rook. } (38... Kf4 39. c4 Rxe2 40. Kxe2 Ke4 41. c5 { (forces Black to go after the Pawn, and gives White two spare moves) } 41... Kd5 42. Ke3 Kxc5 43. Ke4) 39. c4 Rd8+ 40. Kc3 Rc8 { The Rook stops the advance of the Pawn, and is prepared to check the King
whenever it emerges from behind the Pawn. } 41. Kb4 Rb8+ { This puts up the most resistance, as a single wasted move simplifies the
win for White. } (41... Kf4 42. c5 { (once the Pawn reaches c5, there are no problems) } { [%csl Gc5] } 42... Rb8+ 43. Ka5 Rc8 44. Kb6 Rb8+ 45. Kc7 Rh8 46. c6 Rh7+ 47. Kb8 Rh8+ 48. Kb7) 42. Ka5 { Note how the King zig-zags. It is the key to the win in this type of
ending. } 42... Rc8 (42... Ra8+ 43. Kb6 Rb8+ (43... Rc8 44. c5) 44. Kc7 { [%cal Gc4c5] }) 43. Kb5 Rb8+ 44. Ka6 Rc8 45. Rc2! { Threatens to advance the Pawn. Black’s King can now approach, but it’s
too late. } 45... Ke5 (45... Ra8+ 46. Kb7 Rg8 47. c5) (45... Rc7 46. Kb6 Rc8 47. c5) (45... Rc5 46. Kb6 Rc8 47. c5) 46. Kb7 Rc5 47. Kb6 { The strategy may be relatively simple, but Schlechter’s clear and concise
play makes the game a fine piece of instruction. } (47. Rc8 c5 48. Ke6 c6 49. Kd6 c7 50. Kd7 Rd2+ 51. Ke7 Kb7) (47. Kd6 Rd2+) 1-0


