Steinitz defense } (7... O-O { Delay may lead him in the follow ing trap, discovered by Tarrasch } 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8 Raxd8 11. Nxe5 Bxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Nd3 f5 14. f3 Bc5+ 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Bg5 Rd5 17. Be7 { 1-0 (17) Tarrasch, S-Marco,G Dresden 1892 }) 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Bxb5 10. Nxb5 O-O 11. Bg5 { A strong move, but Capablanca found a better one, which led to a
brilliant finish against Fonaroff. } (11. Qc3 c6 12. Nd4 Nd7 13. Nf5 Bf6 14. Qg3 { 1-0 (22) Capablanca,J-Fonaroff,M New York 1918 }) 11... Ng4 { Black aims to simplify the position by exchanging pieces whenever he can
do so. } 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. c4 { This will strengthen the position of the Knight when it eventually
reaches d5. } 13... a6 14. Nc3 Qe5 { Now the threat of 15 … ♕xh2+ forces White to exchange Queens. } { [%csl Rh2] } 15. Qxe5 dxe5 (15... Nxe5 { (to centralize the Knight), White pro tects the c-Pawn by } 16. b3 { and then plays 17 f4, driving the Knight back and out of
play. } { [%cal Gf2f4] }) 16. Nd5! { Simple and strong! The chief threat is not 17
♘xc7, as the reply 17 … ♖ac8 regains the Pawn for Black, but 17 h3, to
which the retreat 17 … ♘h6 renders the Knight hors de combat, while the alternative 17 … ♘f6 allows an exchange by 18 ♘xf6+, which breaks up Black’s
Pawn position. } { [%csl Rc7,Rg4][%cal Gh2h3] } 16... c6 { Plausible, but not the best way to evict the Knight from its fine
outpost, Black’s d6 square is slightly weakened. It is remarkable that this
imperceptible weakness is enough to cost him the game. } (16... Nf6 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Rad1 Rad8 { left White with only a minimal advantage. }) 17. Ne7+ Kh8 { Now White must guard against 18 … g6, which might
leave his Knight stranded. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Gg7g6] } 18. Nf5 Rad8 19. Rad1 { There is only one open file, so both sides dispute its possession } 19... g6 20. Nd6 { Driven out from the outpost d5, the Knight establishes a
more effective one at d6. The immediate threat is 21 ♘xf7+, winning the
exchange. } { [%cal Gd6f7] } 20... Rd7 { Protecting the b-Pawn (which also was attacked) by 20 …
♖b8 would be inferior, as that surrenders the d-file to White. } { [%csl Yb7,Yf7] } 21. c5! { Very strong! The advance of the Pawn supports the
outpost, provides a useful square (c4) for the convenience of the Knight,
and fixes Black’s Pawns on the Queen side. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Yd6c4] } 21... Kg8 (21... Rfd8 22. Nxf7+ { [%csl Rd8,Rh8][%cal Yd1d8] }) 22. Nc4! { Discovers an attack on the Rook, and also threatens to win the e-Pawn by
driving off its defender with 23 f3. } 22... Rfd8 { Black decides to give up the e-Pawn for the sake of establishing a Rook
on the seventh rank. } (22... Re7 23. Rd6 { [%cal Ge1d1] }) 23. Rxd7 Rxd7 24. f3 { Finally this move comes in, and with great effect. The Knight is forced
