{ The Roving Rook One of the most beautiful Rook endings ever played (and
that qualifies it to be instructive as well as entertaining) is from a
little-known game of Pillsbury’s. It is characterized by fierce energy, the sort with which Pillsbury so often demolished his opponent’s position
‘root and branch’ in the midgame. Despite its typical vigor, the ending is not lacking in finesse, and a study of its fine points will add polish to anyone’s play. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { Pillsbury was the first master to realize the strength of this opening,
which he once described as “a Ruy Lopez on the King side.” } 4... Be7 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Rc1 { A strong line of play. The Rook bears down on the c-file, which will be
opened, sooner or later, by an exchange of Pawns. } 7... a6 8. cxd5 (8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 10. Bd3 Bb7 { By this means, the Queen Bishop would be developed,
generally a problem in this opening. } { [%cal Gc7c5] }) 8... exd5 9. Bd3 c6 (9... b5 10. O-O Bb7 { the Bishop has very little scope, the diagonal being blocked by one of
Black’s own Pawns. }) 10. O-O Re8 11. Bb1 Ne4 { Superficially attractive, this at tempt to free the position is not as
good as it looks } (11... Nf8) 12. Bf4 Ndf6 (12... Bd6 { loses a Pawn by } 13. Bxe4 Bxf4 (13... dxe4 14. Bxd6 exf3 15. Qxf3) 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. exf4) 13. Ne5 { White’s pieces are strongly placed, in a formation favored by Pillsbury. } 13... Bf5 14. f3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bxb1 16. Rxb1 Ra7 { An awkward move, but how else protect the Knight Pawn? } (16... Rb8 17. Nxc6! { [%csl Rb8][%cal Gf4b8,Yb1b8] }) (16... Qc8 { is not an attractive move to make, the Queen being relegated to the
defense of a Pawn. }) 17. Qd3 Bd6 { Black is anxious to drive off the annoying Knight, but finds (after
White’s next move) that the Knight is not ready to leave. A better try
might have been 17 … ♘d7 instead } (17... Nd7) 18. Bg5! h6 (18... Bxe5 19. dxe5 Rxe5 20. Qd4 Qb8 21. Bf4 { [%csl Rb8,Re5][%cal Yf4b8] }) 19. Bh4 { [%cal Gd3f5,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] } 19... g5 { Desperate measures, but White was threatening to increase the pressure by
20 ♕f5, followed by 21 g4 and 22 g5. } 20. Bg3 Nh5 21. Qf5 { [%csl Rf7][%cal Ye5g6,Gf5f7] } 21... Qf6 { A natural move, but it meets with a surprising refutation } 22. Ng4! { This pretty move wins a Pawn against any defense } 22... Qxf5 (22... Qe6 23. Bxd6 Qxd6 24. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5] } 24... f6 (24... Ng7 25. Nf6+ Kf8 (25... Kh8 26. Qh7#) 26. Nxe8) (24... Qe7 25. Nxh6+ Kg7 26. Qxg5+ Qxg5 27. fxg5 { [%csl Rf7,Rh5][%cal Gg2g4] }) 25. Qg6+ Ng7 26. Nxh6+) 23. Nxh6+ Kh7 24. Nxf5 { see? } 24... Bxg3 25. hxg3 b5 26. Kf2! { A fine move! This guarding of the Pawns at
g3 and e3 frees the Knight for active duty. It also makes it possible for
one of the Rooks to utilize the h-file for attack. } { [%csl Ye3,Gf5,Yg3][%cal Gf1h1] } 26... Kg6 27. Rh1 { This is better than defending the Knight by 27 g4. White is willing to
exchange pieces, being a Pawn ahead. } 27... Kxf5 (27... Ng7 { White forces mate in problem-like style by } 28. Rh6+ Kxf5 29. g4#) 28. Rxh5 (28. g4+!? { [is also interesting] }) 28... Rae7 29. Rh6! f6 (29... Rxe3 30. g4+ Kf4 31. g3#) 30. Re1 { A subtle move, which shortly brings about an exchange of Rooks. } 30... a5 31. g4+ Ke6 32. f4 gxf4 33. exf4+ Kd7 34. Rxe7+ Kxe7 35. Rh7+ { Seizes the seventh rank, the road to happiness for a Rook. } { [%csl Gh7] } 35... Kd6 36. Rf7 Ke6 (36... Re6 37. f5 { [%csl Rf6] }) 37. Ra7 { “Notice the scope of White’s Rook,” says the Reverend Cunnington, “moving
