{ Web of Black Squares Certain squares on the chessboard seem to be vital
nerve centers. Control of them gives a player a tremendous positional
advantage - nearly always a decisive one. In the following game, Schlechter’s overall strategy is impressive, but never more so than in the way he
utilizes the key squares e5, f6 and h6. He occupies the latter two with his pieces, and gets a powerful grip on the King side. As for e5, not only does Schlechter secure possession of that square, but he makes use of it as a convenient jumping-off place for his pieces. It is occupied in turn
by a Knight, the Queen, a Pawn, and then the other Knight. When the King himself threatens to assume command from there, it is an indication to the opponent that it’s time to resign. The game is a large-scale master -piece, with the action taking place over the full range of the board - the King side, the center, and the Queen side. It is undoubtedly the greatest game Schlechter ever played, and for that matter, one of the greatest games anybody ever played }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 f5 { Black’s arrangement of Pawns is known as the Stonewall Formation. Its
purpose is to create a strong Pawn support for a Knight at e5, and with the
center made secure, to play for an attack on the King side. There are two drawbacks to the Stonewall. One is that the square e5 is weakened: an
enemy piece posted there could not be driven away by Pawns. The second is the weakening of Black’s Queen Bishop, whose range of action is restricted by the Pawns standing on white squares. } 4. Nf3 c6 5. Bf4 Bd6 6. e3! { This is stronger than the immediate exchange of Bishops } (6. Bxd6 Qxd6 { Black continues by … ♘d7 and … e5, freeing
his Queen Bishop. } { [%csl Yc8][%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5] }) 6... Nf6 { Black in turn does not care to exchange Bishops } (6... Bxf4 7. exf4 { White’s grip on e5 could not be shaken off. } { [%csl Ge5] }) 7. Bd3 Qc7 { Hopes, with his threat of winning a Pawn by 8 … ♗xf4 9 exf4
♕xf4, to induce White to exchange Bishops. } { [%csl Rf4] } 8. g3! { White is not to be tempted. Instead, he reinforces the position of his
Bishop. } 8... O-O 9. O-O Ne4 { A fine outpost for the Knight, if the beast can
manage to stay there. But White has f3 in reserve, whenever he chooses to
dislodge the Knight. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Gf2f3] } 10. Qb3 { The Queen develops with a threat } 10... Kh8 11. Rac1 { [%csl Rd5] } 11... Bxf4 { Rendered impatient by the menac ing aspect of the position (one threat
being 12 cxd5 exd5 13 ♘xd5), Black decides to clear away a couple of
pieces. } 12. exf4 { The result though, is that Black is saddled with a backward e-Pawn on an
open file (and the mortality rate on backward Pawns is high). } 12... Qf7 13. Ne5 { This Knight, which cannot be driven away by Pawns, is powerfully placed
at e5 - one of the vital nerve centers of the chessboard. Black’s position
is the inferior one at this point, for two reasons: (1) His black squares are weak, greatly due to the absence of the Bishop controlling those
squares. (2) His Queen Bishop has little freedom of movement, since it is hemmed in by Pawns occupying white squares - the color on which the Bishop travels. } 13... Qe7 14. Bxe4! { Surprising - he closes the e-file! } (14. Qc2 { evicting the Knight from its outpost, but Schlechter has a
more effective continuation } { [%cal Gf2f3] }) (14. f3 Nd2) 14... fxe4 15. f3 { But this move will not only pry it open, but rid White of his doubled
Pawn as well! } 15... exf3 16. Rce1 { This is stronger than recapturing the Pawn. Black must lose a move now to
avoid the threat } 16... Qc7 17. Qa3 { Another restraining move } 17... Kg8 (17... Nd7 18. Qe7 { is practically fatal }) 18. Rxf3 Na6 19. b3 Qd8 20. c5 { Increases the pressure on the black squares. The square d6 (from White’s
side) is now inaccessible to Black’s pieces. } 20... Nc7 21. Qb2 Bd7 22. Qc2 Qe7 23. Ref1 Rae8 24. g4 Bc8 25. Rh3 { Threatens mate on the move, and forces a loosening of the Pawn position
around Black’s King. } 25... g6 { The only move, since 25 … h6 loses the exchange after the
reply 26 ♘g6. But the advance of the g-Pawn irreparably weakens Black’s f6
and h6 squares. Eventually, White will plant pieces firmly on those squares. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh6] } (25... h6 26. Ng6) 26. b4 { “It is surprising” says Réti, “that White suddenly begins to attack on
the Queen side. But that is the epic of Schlechter’s game. He carries out
operations apparently not concerted on different parts of the board, so that one has the impression that a game with no clear preconceived objective
is in progress. And it is only at the end that one perceives for the first time the connection of things seemingly dis connected, with the result that the game is rounded off into one great homogeneous whole.” } 26... Qf6 27. Rhf3 Re7 { Black defends patiently. An at tempt to open the position would be
disastrous } (27... g5 28. fxg5 Qxg5 29. Rxf8+ Rxf8 30. Rxf8+ Kxf8 31. Qf2+ Kg7 (31... Ke7 32. Qf7+ Kd8 33. Qf8+ Ne8 34. Nf7+) 32. Qf7+ Kh6 (32... Kh8 33. Qf8+ Qg8 34. Nf7#) 33. Qf8+ Qg7 34. g5+) 28. a4 a6 { The next few moves need a bit of explanation. Schlechter wants to post
his Queen Knight at h6, supported by a Pawn at g5. If he plays 29 g5 at
once, the reply would be 29 … ♕f5. To prevent even this much counter-play, Sch lechter will swing the Queen Knight over to e3 (by way of d1), then
play 29 g5, and follow that with 30 ♘g4 and 31 ♘h6+. } 29. Nd1! (29. g5 Qf5) 29... Rg7 30. Ne3 { [%csl Rf5][%cal Gg4g5] } 30... Qe7 (30... h6 31. g5 hxg5 32. N3g4 Qe7 (32... Qf5 33. Nh6+) 33. Nh6+ Kh8 34. Rh3 { [%csl Ye7][%cal Gh6f7,Gh3h8,Yh6f5] } 34... Rh7 35. Nxg6+) 31. g5 { The encirclement continues, leaving Black with less and less moves. } 31... Bd7 32. N3g4 Be8 33. Nh6+ Kh8 34. Qe2 Qd8 35. Neg4 Bd7 36. Qe5 Ne8 37. Rh3 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gh3h4,Gf1f3,Gf3h3] } 37... Qc7 { Black is confined to the first two ranks, and tries to get some freedom
by exchanging Queens. Against passive play, White could prepare a mating
combination } 38. Nf6! { White is now in full control of the key squares. } 38... Qxe5 { Black must go through with this exchange } (38... Qd8 39. Nxh7 Kxh7 40. Nf7+ { [%csl Rd8][%cal Gh3h7,Gf7d8] }) 39. fxe5 { And now White has an open f-file on which to double his Rooks. } 39... Re7 40. Rhf3 Nxf6 { Practically forced, in view of the various threats } 41. Rxf6 Rxf6 42. exf6! { The proper way to take the Rook. Now the key
square e5 is available to the Knight, and finally the King. } { [%csl Ye5][%cal Gh6g4,Gg4e5] } 42... Re8 43. Nf7+ Kg8 44. Ne5 { [%cal Gf6f7] } 44... Rd8 { Forced, to save the Bishop and to prevent loss of the Rook by 45 f7+. } 45. Kg2 { The King is to be brought closer to the center before White breaks
through decisively. } 45... Kf8 46. h4 Be8 (46... Bc8 47. h5 gxh5 48. Rh1 { lets the Rook become more active. }) 47. Kf3 Bf7 48. Kf4 Ke8 49. Rb1! { The maneuvering was all on the King side of the board, but the
breakthrough comes on the Queenside! } 49... Kf8 50. b5 { 1-0 Black resigns. } (50. axb5 axb5 51. Be8 bxc6 52. Bxc6 (52. bxc6 Rb7) 52... Nxc6 53. bxc6 Ke5 54. Re8 Rb7 { A strategical masterpiece! Outwardly the game may offer little glamour or
excitement, but to the connoisseur it is a complete delight. }) 1-0


