{ Endgame arithmetic In an innocent-looking position, Reshevsky, alert as a
cat, pounces on a Pawn (something he has done a thousand times before). As
suddenly as he won the Pawn, Reshevsky hastens to return it, and bring the position to an ending where Pawns are even. The rest (though a master might
consider it just a matter of counting up moves) is a bit of endgame artistry }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Ng3 (5. Nxf6+ gxf6 { in reply weakens Black’s Pawn position on the King side } (5... exf6 { lets White have four Pawns to three on the Queenside. })) 5... e5 { Disputes the center at once! Another way of doing so (in order to get rid
of the Queen Pawn) is } (5... c5 6. Nf3 e6 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. a3 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. b4 Be7 12. Bb2 Bb7) 6. Be3 (6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Ng4 { and Black regains his Pawn. }) (6. Nf3 { Somewhat stronger than Mieses’s 6 ♗e3 move is 6 ♘f3 (Knights before
Bishops!) a line of play with which Alekhine beat Tartakover brilliantly at
Kecskemet in 1927 (but then Alekhine always beat Tartakover brilliantly!). } 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Qe2+ Be7 9. Be3 c5 10. Ndf5 O-O 11. Qc4 Re8 12. Bd3 b6 13. O-O-O Ba6 14. Nh6+ gxh6 15. Bxh7+ Nxh7 16. Qg4+ Kh8 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Qe4 Nc6 19. Qxc6 Bf8 20. Nf5 Bc4 21. Bxh6 Bd5 22. Qc7 Rac8 23. Qf4 Rc6 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 25. Qe5+ Nf6 26. Nd6 { 1-0 (26) Alekhine,A-Tartakower, S Kecskemet 1927 }) 6... exd4 7. Qxd4 Qa5+ 8. Qd2 (8. Bd2 Qd5 9. Qxd5 Nxd5 10. Bc4 $14) 8... Bb4! { Forces 9 c3, and the resultant weakening of White’s d3 square. } 9. c3 { [%csl Rd3] } 9... Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. N1e2 c5! { This permits the Queen Knight to develop at c6, the ideal
square. } { [%cal Gb8c6] } 12. Nf5 { This looks attractive, since it assures White of the two Bishops, but …
(1) He cannot keep the Bishops very long, and, (2) It allows Black time to
get his Queen side pieces into play quickly. } 12... Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Nc6 14. O-O Rad8 { An attack on the Queen which compels White to lose a move. } 15. Qc2 g6 { After this, White must either allow the exchange of the Bishop, or move
it to h3, where it is awkwardly placed. } 16. Be4 (16. Bh3 { [%csl Rh3] }) (16. Bd3 Ne5 { [%csl Rd3] }) 16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Rfe8 18. Qc2 c4! { Very good, since it brings pressure to bear on the square d3,
which was weakened by White’s ninth move. There is now the possibility of
posting a piece at d3, where it has the strong support of the c-pawn. } { [%csl Gd3] } 19. b4 { An impatient move, which weakens the c-Pawn. The position is
not a happy one, but 19 ♘d4 might have put up more fight. } { [%csl Rc3] } (19. Nd4) 19... Qc7 20. Rfd1 Ne5 { [%cal Ge5d3] } 21. Bf4 { Pins the Knight, which was on its way to d3. } { [%cal Yf4c7] } 21... Bd6 22. Nd4 (22. Bg3 Nd3 23. Bxd6 Rxd6 24. Nc1 Ne1 25. Qa4 b5 26. Qxb5 Rxd1! 27. Qxe8+ Kg7 28. Qe2? Nf3# { double check and mate! }) 22... Nf3+ 23. Nxf3 Bxf4 24. g3 { This is usually a bad formation in Castled positions, since the white
squares are weakened by the Pawn’s advance. This weakening contri butes to
White’s downfall, although it is difficult to see at this stage how Black can exploit his advantages. } 24... Bh6 { The Bishop prepares to retreat to g7, where it
commands the long diagonal, and has a target in the c-Pawn. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Gh6g7] } 25. a4 Bg7 26. b5 { This only helps Black, who now gets his Queen into more active play. } 26... Qc5! 27. Rac1 Rd5! { Indicating that he intends to double Rooks on the d-file. To
prevent this, White must exchange Rooks. } { [%cal Ge8d8] } 28. Rxd5 Qxd5 { Now the Knight is attacked, and there is a
threat of invading the position by 29 … ♖d8, followed by 30 … ♕d3 } { [%csl Rd3,Rf3][%cal Ge8d8] } 29. Nd4 { This loses a Pawn, but the alternatives are not satisfactory } (29. Nd2 Re2 30. Rd1 Bh6 31. f4? Qg2#) (29. Kg2 Rd8 30. Re1 Qd3 31. Qxd3 cxd3 32. c4 Rc8 33. Rd1 Rxc4 34. Rxd3 Rxa4) 29... Bxd4 30. cxd4 Re4! { Attacks the d-Pawn twice, and cleverly prevents the capture of
his c-Pawn. } { [%csl Rd4] } (30... Qxd4 31. Qxc4 Re1+ 32. Kg2! { But Reshevsky has a little zwischenzug up his sleeve! }) 31. Rd1 (31. Qxc4 Re1+!! { [%csl Rg2] }) 31... Rxd4 32. Rxd4 Qxd4 33. Kf1 Kf8 34. a5 { After this move, it looks as though we were in for a long, dreary ending,
with Black’s King facing countless checks as soon as he comes into the
open, but Reshevsky finds an artistic way to simplify matters and finish off his opponent. He forces an exchange of Queens, and throws in his precious
passed Pawn as a bonus. Such is the power of a superior position! } (34. Ke1 Ke7 35. Qe2+ Kd6 { and the threat of exchanging Queens, or of advancing further with the
