which enabled Mieses to exploit his positional advantages - pressure on the
open file, and a Pawn majority on the Queenside. I give the continuation here, not only because it is interesting, but because it is rare that
Rubinstein the Giant-killer is beaten so quickly and effectively } 11... Nxc3 12. Rxc3 c4 13. Ne5 O-O 14. b3 Qb4 15. Qd2 Rac8 16. Rd1 b5 17. f4 Nxe5 18. fxe5 a5 19. bxc4 Rxc4 20. Rb3 Qa4 21. e3 Rfc8 22. Bf1 Rc2 23. Qe1 b4 24. Bd3 Qxa2! { 0-1 (24) Rubinstein,A-Mieses,J Berlin/ Hannover/ Frankfurt 1909 }) 11... Nxd4! (11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qd7 14. f4 O-O 15. Qc2) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. e3 (13. Bxe4 Bh3 { and suddenly three of White’s pieces are in danger. }) 13... Nf3+ 14. Nxf3 exf3 15. Qxf3 O-O 16. Rfc1 { “White’s inactivity on his stronger wing took away all the chances he had
