{ Cornucopia of Ideas This is one of those unknown masterpieces that
bubbles over with good things. Among the strategic ideas you will see is a
position held in complete restraint by virtue of control of the white squares, permitting the King to wander casually over to the Queen side as
a prelude to the decisive combination. After a tactical interlude, involving a sacrifice of the exchange, there follows a vivid demonstration of the power of a Rook on the seventh rank. And, since chess is cruel, there is a massacre of the innocents - the hap less Pawns being the victims }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 { Restraint is the essence of the Nimzo-Indian - a sound, fighting de fense
to the Queen Pawn Opening. Black plays to prevent e4 by White, first by
pinning the Queen Knight, and second by bearing down on e4 with his Queen Bishop, from the square b7. Black also retains the possibility of saddling
his opponent with a doubled Pawn by … ♗xc3, thus providing him with a good object of attack. } 4. e3 b6 5. Be2 Bb7 6. Bf3? { A strategic error, since the ex change of Bishops is to Black’s
advantage. He can now play to gain control of e4 and c4, squares which have
lost the protection of the white-squared Bishop. } 6... Bxf3 7. Nxf3 O-O 8. O-O d5 { The beginning of Black’s long-range plan to get a grip on
e4 and c4. He intends to remove both of White’s Knights, and leave him with
a Bishop hampered by Pawns standing on black squares. } { [%csl Gc4,Ge4] } 9. Qb3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 (10. Qxc3 Ne4) 10... Nc6! { The Knight’s ultimate aim is to occupy the square
c4. For the moment its threat is to win a Pawn by 17 … ♘a5 } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gc6a5] } 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Qa4 Qd7! { Another developing move with gain of time! } { [%cal Gc6a5] } 13. cxd5 (13. h3 Nxd4 14. Qxd7 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 Nxd7) 13... exd5 14. Rfd1 { Blissfully unaware of any danger, White makes a normal developing move.
It turns out to be the decisive mistake, since it enables Black to carry
out his object (which I have indicated several times before) of getting a grip on c4, one of the weakened white squares. } 14... Na5! 15. Qxd7 Nxd7 16. Bb4 Nc4 { Threatens to steal the Bishop by 17 … a5. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ga7a5] } 17. a4 a5 18. Ba3 Re6! { A strange move, the purpose of which will become evident in a move or
two. } 19. Nd2 Nxd2 20. Rxd2 Rc6 { Now we see what the Rook is up to - restraint! White
is not to be allowed to free his game by means of c4 or e4. One may ask why
the power of a Rook is to be spent on preventing a Pawn from moving. The answer is that the Rook is doing this only temporarily. The Knight will work
its way over to d6, and relieve the Rook of that duty. } { [%cal Rc3c4,Re3e4] } 21. Bb2 { White would rather keep the Bishop at a3, in order to capture the Knight
on its arrival at d6, but the Bishop must retreat. } (21. Rc2 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Ga3f8,Yd7f6,Yf6e4,Ye4d6] } 21... Rc4 { the a-Pawn, and forces the Bishop to retreat
anyway if White is to save the Pawn. } { [%csl Ra4][%cal Ya3b2,Yb2c1] }) 21... Re8 22. Kf1 Nf6 23. Rc2 Ne4 24. Ke2 Nd6 25. Kd3 f5 { Tightens the grip on the squares e4 and c4. On the former,
Black bears down with Rook, Knight and two Pawns, on the latter with Rook,
Knight and Pawn } { [%csl Gc4,Ge4] } 26. f3 Nc4 { Attacks the e-Pawn once more, and ties White’s pieces down to
its defense. } { [%csl Re3] } 27. Bc1 Rce6 28. Re2 Kf7 29. Re1 c6 30. Rb1 R8e7! { This makes it possible for
the King to move behind the Rook on its journey to a6. Once the King
reaches that square, the plan is to advance … b5, and after axb5, axb5, to create a passed Pawn on the a-file. } { [%cal Gf7e8,Gd7c7,Gc7b7,Gb7a6,Yb6b5] } 31. Re2 Ke8 32. h3 h5 33. Rb3 Kd7 34. Re1 Kc7 35. g3 Kb7 36. Bd2 Ka6 37. Reb1 { This is intended to hinder Black from advancing his b- Pawn. That Black
can do so though, with favorable chances for himself, may be seen from this
analysis } 37... Rxe3+! { There is a combination in the position though - an effective one. And
Black finds it! } (37... b5 38. axb5+ cxb5 39. Rxb5 (39. Bc1 Rxe3+! 40. Bxe3 Rxe3+ 41. Kc2 a4 42. Rb4 Rxf3) 39... Rxe3+ 40. Bxe3 Rxe3+ 41. Kc2 Na3+ 42. Kd2 Nxb1+ 43. Rxb1 Rxf3 { and Black has the better of it. }) 38. Bxe3 Rxe3+ 39. Kc2 Re2+ 40. Kd1 (40. Kd3 Rd2#) (40. Kc1 Re1+ 41. Kc2 Rxb1 42. Rxb1 (42. Kxb1 Nd2+) 42... Na3+ { leads to a pure Pawn ending with Black a Pawn ahead - and that’s the
easiest kind of ending to win. }) 40... Ra2 { This leaves White curiously helpless; it's now quite difficult to remove
Rook from 7th rank } 41. g4 (41. Rc1 { [%cal Gc1c2] } 41... Rxa4 { [%cal Gc1c2,Yc4e3] } 42. Ke2 Ra2+) 41... fxg4 42. fxg4 h4 43. g5 Rxa4 { [%cal Ga4a2,Ga2h2,Gh2h3] } (43... Rh2) 44. Ke2 { This results in loss of the exchange but other moves permit 44 … ♖a2
followed by 45 … ♖h2 and 46 … ♖xh3, securing Black a passed Pawn on each
side of the board. } 44... Ra2+ 45. Kf3 { This is not a blunder, as every thing else is hopeless. White’s only
chance lies in getting over to the King side, to acquire a passed Pawn of
his own. } 45... Nd2+ { A family check, with so few pieces on the board! } 46. Kg4 Nxb3 47. Rxb3 a4 48. Rb1 Rc2 49. Kxh4 Rxc3 { The removal of this Pawn secures Black two connected passed Pawns, with
one ready to protect the other. } 50. g6 a3 51. Kg4 Rd3 52. h4 Rxd4+ 53. Kg5 Rd2 54. Ra1 a2 55. h5 b5 56. h6 gxh6+ 57. Kxh6 Rh2+ 58. Kg5 Rg2+ 59. Kf6 b4 60. g7 b3 61. Kf7 Rxg7+ 62. Kxg7 Kb5 (62... b2? 63. Rxa2+ Kb5 64. Rxb2+ { might result in Black’s giving up chess! }) 63. Kf6 b2 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


