{ Endgame duel: Knight against Rook This is a glorious game of Botvinnik’s,
worthy to rank with his famous victory over Capablanca at Avro in 1938. The
game is fascinating through out its length, from the opening that Botvinnik conducts in original style, through the midgame where the sacrifice of the
exchange permits his Rook to dominate the board, to the ending where his agile Knight dances rings around the opposing Rook. A great deal may be learned from this game, but more than that, it is a game that one plays over and over again with renewed pleasure each time, as one takes delight in reading
over and over again a fantastic tale of John Collier’s or a priceless pastiche by Perelman. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Qd7 6. Qxc4 Qc6 { Black insists on exchanging Queens! White must comply, his Queen Bishop
being unprotected. } 7. Nbd2 Qxc4 8. Nxc4 Bb4+ { Black wants to exchange Bishops too, but a preferable alternative was 8 …
♗e7 (simple development) or 8 … c5 (attack on the center). } 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nfxd2! { Clever play! The long diagonal is cleared for the Bishop, and there are
prospects of setting up a strong Pawn center with e4. } 10... Nc6 11. e3 Nb4 12. Ke2! { Simple and strong! The King meets the threat of 12 … ♘c2+ by coming to
the center. This is perfectly safe now that Queens are off the board, and
there is little danger of running into a mating attack. } 12... Bd7 13. Bg2 Bc6 14. f3 { The Bishop is blocked temporarily, for the sake of building up a Pawn
center. } 14... Nd7 15. a3 Nd5 16. e4 N5b6 17. Na5 { Threatens to ruin Black’s Pawn position by playing 18 ♘xc6. } 17... Bb5+ 18. Ke3 O-O-O { The b-Pawn is now protected, and Black prepares to drive off the annoying
Knight at a5 by 19 …♘b8 and 20 … ♘c6. } 19. Rhc1 (19. Rac1 { The action will be on the Queen side, and the Queen Rook is needed where
it is, to support an advance of the a-Pawn. This Pawn has an important role
to play in the plan to disorganize Black’s forces. }) 19... Nb8 20. b3 Bd7 { A prudent retreat. Vidmar is aware of the danger inherent in a cramped
position, and would very much like to free his game by bring ing about an
exchange of pieces. But if he plays 20 … ♘c6, there follows 21 a4 ♘xa5 22 axb5, and his Knight at a5 is doomed. At this point, the dilettante, who
is always on the lookout for brilliancies, might say to himself, “Wouldn’t it be nice if I could play 21 ♘dc4 and then 22 ♘d6 mate?” The master player, I assure you, gives this possibility little more than a passing thought. What concerns him, at this and other stages, is that all his pieces be
in active play. If they are not effectively placed, he moves them (by retreat if neces sary) to squares where they can exert some influence. He gives more thought to this, which is the substance of position play, than to the planning of intricate combinations. Botvinnik’s next move brings the Bishop into more active play, though all it seems to do is keep a long diagonal under observation. } (20... Nc6 21. a4 Nxa5 22. axb5 { [%csl Ra5] }) 21. Bf1 Nc6 22. Nxc6 Bxc6 23. a4! { This would split up Black’s Pawns, making them
vulnerable to attack, and at the same time open a file for White’s Queen
Rook. } { [%cal Ga4a5,Ga5a6,Ga6b7] } 23... Be8 24. a5 Na8 { An unhappy retreat, but the Knight guards the Bishop Pawn from the
corner. Black’s pieces are now all on the first rank, and while the
position might have pleased Steinitz, it would take the patience and defensive skill of a Steinitz to keep it intact. } (24... Nd7 25. a6 b6 26. Rc3 Kb8 27. Rac1 Rc8 28. Nc4 { [%csl Rc8][%cal Gc4d6] } 28... Rd8 29. Na3 Rc8 30. Nb5 $18) 25. a6 b6 26. b4 Kb8 { Black prepares to advance the c-Pawn so that the Knight can get back into
the game } (26... c6 27. Bb5 Kc7 { (blocks the Knight, but how else save the Pawn?) } { [%csl Ra8] } 28. Ra3 Rd6 29. Rac3 { and after 30 e5 the Pawn will fall. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Ge4e5] }) 27. Rc3 c6 28. Rac1 f6! { A preventive measure against 29 ♘c4 followed by 30 ♘e5. The attempt to
mobilize his own Knight would be premature } (28... Nc7 29. b5 Nxb5 30. Bxb5 cxb5 31. Rc7 Bd7 32. Rb7+ Ka8 33. Rcc7 { establishes both of White’s Rooks on the seventh rank, with a winning
position. }) 29. Nb1! Bd7 30. Na3 { Intending to break in with unremitting pressure } { [%cal Gb4b5] } 30... Nc7 (30... b5 31. Nb1 Nc7 32. Ra3 { Once the Knight is established on this strong
outpost (c5), the position would be definitely won for White. } { [%cal Gb1d2,Gd2b3] }) 31. b5! { “It is worth giving up a Pawn,” says Fine, “to get a Rook on the seventh
rank.” } 31... Nxb5 32. Bxb5 cxb5 33. Rc7! { The situation is critical, and could lead to checkmate for Black. } 33... Rc8 { Black misses his chance! } (33... b4 34. Rb7+ Ka8 35. Rcc7) (33... Bc8 34. Nxb5 Rd7! 35. Rxd7 Bxd7 36. Nxa7 Kxa7 37. Rc7+ Kxa6 38. Rxd7 Rc8! { probably draws, since he dominates the open file, and has a dangerous
passed Pawn. }) 34. Rb7+ Ka8 35. Rxd7 { Fine play! Botvinnik sacrifices the exchange for the sake of main taining
a Rook on the seventh rank. } 35... Rxc1 36. Nxb5 Rhc8 { After Black’s move, both of his Rooks are tied down to the c-file. } (36... Rg8 37. Rxa7+ Kb8 38. Rb7+ Ka8 (38... Kc8 39. Nd6+ Kd8 40. a7 Ra1 41. Rb8+ Kc7 (41... Kd7) (41... Ke7 42. Rxg8 Rxa7 43. Rxg7+) 42. Rxg8 Rxa7 43. Nb5+) 39. Nc7+ Rxc7 40. Rxc7) 37. Rxg7 h6 38. Rxa7+ Kb8 39. Rb7+ Ka8 40. Ra7+ { This gains time on the clock, and also demonstrates the opponent’s
helplessness to him - a favorite device of Tarrasch’s. } 40... Kb8 41. Rb7+ Ka8 42. g4 { Preparing to fix Black’s h-Pawn by h4 and h5. } 42... e5 { A desperate move, since it affords White the opportunity to get a passed
Pawn, but Black wants the square c4 for one of his Rooks. He intends either
to drive the Knight away, or force an exchange of Rooks. } 43. d5 R1c5 44. Ra7+ Kb8 45. Rb7+ Ka8 46. Rxb6 Rb8 { This will end the white Rook’s career. } 47. Rxb8+ Kxb8 48. a7+ Kb7! { Vidmar puts up a hard fight } (48... Ka8 49. d6 Rc8 (49... Rc1 50. d7 Rd1 51. Nc7+ Kxa7 52. Nd5 { [%cal Gd7d8] }) 50. Kd3! Kb7 (50... Rc1 51. Nc3 $18) 51. Nc7 Kxa7 52. Kc4 Kb6 53. Kd5 $18 Rd8 54. Ne6 Rd7 55. Nc5 Rd8 56. d7 Kc7 57. Ne6+ Kxd7 58. Nxd8 Kxd8 59. Ke6 $18) 49. Nd6+! (49. d6 Rc8 50. Kd3 Rc1 51. Nc3 Ra1 { and Black still needs subduing }) 49... Kxa7 50. Ne8 Kb6 51. Nxf6 { [%cal Gf6d7] } 51... Rc3+ 52. Kf2 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gf6d7] } 52... Rc7 { [%cal Rf6d7] } 53. h4 Rf7 54. Nh5 Kc7 55. g5! hxg5 56. hxg5 Rh7 57. Nf6 Rh2+ (57... Rg7 58. Ne8+) (57... Rf7 58. f4 exf4 59. e5 $18) 58. Kg3 Rh1 { Hoping to get behind the Pawn, but White puts an end to that aspiration. } 59. Kg2! { Domination! The Rook has only one decent square open to it on the h-file. } 59... Rh8 { The last chance to stop the Pawn } (59... Ra1 60. g6 Ra8 61. g7 Kd6 62. g8=Q) 60. g6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } (60. Rh6 g7 61. Rg6+ Kf2 62. Rxg7 Ne8+) 1-0


